The issue lies in the manual memory management. In C++, you've correctly defined a destructor for `DataBuffer`, but you haven't explicitly deleted the memory in the destructor. You should have `delete[] buffer;` in the destructor to prevent resource leaks.

To fix this, modify the destructor as follows:

```cpp
~DataBuffer() {
    delete[] buffer;
}
```

Also, consider using smart pointers like `unique_ptr` or `shared_ptr` for managing dynamically allocated memory, as they automatically handle memory deallocation. This approach can reduce bugs and prevent memory leaks. 

Another issue is that your program will continue to allocate memory in the `runTask` function without any clean-up, potentially causing your program to run out of memory. You may want to consider re-designing your application to avoid unnecessary allocations.
